    "role": "assistant",
    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n\n<head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n    <title>JavaScript Set Example</title>\n    <style>\n        body {\n            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n            margin: 20px;\n        }\n\n        .set-demo {\n            margin-top: 20px;\n            border: 1px solid #ccc;\n            padding: 10px;\n        }\n\n        .set-output {\n            margin-top: 10px;\n            color: blue;\n        }\n    </style>\n</head>\n\n<body>\n\n    <h1>JavaScript Set Example</h1>\n    <p>A Set is a collection of values where each value must be unique. Let's explore the Set data structure with some examples.</p>\n\n    <div class=\"set-demo\">\n        <h2>Basic Operations with Set</h2>\n        <button id=\"addButton\">Add Element</button>\n        <input type=\"text\" id=\"inputElement\" placeholder=\"Enter an element\" />\n        <button id=\"deleteButton\">Delete Element</button>\n        <button id=\"hasButton\">Check Element</button>\n        <input type=\"text\" id=\"hasInput\" placeholder=\"Check if element exists\" />\n        <button id=\"showSetButton\">Show Set</button>\n        <div class=\"set-output\" id=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n\n    <script>\n        // Create a new Set\n        const mySet = new Set();\n\n        // Function to display the current elements of the set\n        function displaySet() {\n            document.getElementById('output').innerText = `Current Set: [${[...mySet]}]`;\n        }\n\n        // Add element to the set\n        document.getElementById('addButton').addEventListener('click', () => {\n            const element = document.getElementById('inputElement').value;\n            if (element) {\n                mySet.add(element);\n                displaySet();\n                document.getElementById('inputElement').value = '';\n            }\n        });\n\n        // Delete element from the set\n        document.getElementById('deleteButton').addEventListener('click', () => {\n            const element = document.getElementById('inputElement').value;\n            if (element) {\n                mySet.delete(element);\n                displaySet();\n                document.getElementById('inputElement').value = '';\n            }\n        });\n\n        // Check if element exists in the set\n        document.getElementById('hasButton').addEventListener('click', () => {\n            const element = document.getElementById('hasInput').value;\n            const exists = mySet.has(element);\n            alert(exists ? `Yes, \"${element}\" exists in the set.` : `No, \"${element}\" does not exist in the set.`);\n            document.getElementById('hasInput').value = '';\n        });\n\n        // Show current set elements\n        document.getElementById('showSetButton').addEventListener('click', displaySet);\n    </script>\n\n</body>\n\n</html>"
